tity, these students have lived the complexity of their identity from a very young age. In Mixed, a book that will benefit educators, students, and their families, they eloquently and often passionately reveal how they experience their multiracial identity, how their parents' race or ethnicity shaped their childhoods, and how perceptions of their race have affected their relationships.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aRacially mixed youthxEducation (Higher)xNew HampshirexHanover. 0aRacially mixed youthxEducation (Higher)zNew HampshirezHanover. 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh1 aBates, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolsten, Samiir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollado, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Brito, Ana Sofia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarrod, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGomez, Christina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeussner, Ki Mae Ponniah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHsu, Taica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKilkenny, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKondo-Shah, Yuki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLane, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Brien, Dean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrince, Shannon Joyce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShannon, Lola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel